WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.280
[Amit Varma]: How do we judge a political party? One way of doing so would be to see how well it governs

00:00:10.280 --> 00:00:15.520
[Amit Varma]: when it is in power. By this yardstick, all our parties have failed. India has been misgoverned

00:00:15.520 --> 00:00:20.520
[Amit Varma]: throughout the last 74 years, barring brief happy accidents like the liberalisation of

00:00:20.520 --> 00:00:26.680
[Amit Varma]: 1991. Bad economic policies have kept millions of people in poverty for decades longer than

00:00:26.680 --> 00:00:30.920
[Amit Varma]: should have been the case. Our social ruptures have not been healed. If anything, they've

00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:36.800
[Amit Varma]: become worse and new fault lines have sprung up. But perhaps judging a party on governance

00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:42.840
[Amit Varma]: is not fair. It ignores their incentives. A party's incentives are simply to win elections.

00:00:42.840 --> 00:00:48.200
[Amit Varma]: People don't vote on the basis of governance, but on the basis of narratives. Our parties

00:00:48.200 --> 00:00:52.960
[Amit Varma]: have been brilliant at creating narratives, building vote banks, constructing election

00:00:52.960 --> 00:00:59.560
[Amit Varma]: machines of staggering complexity and equally staggering efficiency. And it's so fascinating

00:00:59.560 --> 00:01:08.040
[Amit Varma]: to take a look inside these machines at the nuts and bolts of our great democracy.

00:01:08.040 --> 00:01:13.240
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Scene and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioural

00:01:13.240 --> 00:01:20.520
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:20.520 --> 00:01:24.840
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and The Unseen. My guest today is Shivam Shankar Singh, author of two

00:01:24.840 --> 00:01:30.360
[Amit Varma]: books, How to Win an Indian Election, which came out in 2019 and just released The Art

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:35.680
[Amit Varma]: of Conjuring Alternate Realities, co-written with Anand Venkat Narayan. Shivam's career

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:40.660
[Amit Varma]: graph is fascinating. He was studying economics in the US a decade ago when he got interested

00:01:40.660 --> 00:01:45.400
[Amit Varma]: in Indian politics. The India Against Corruption movement filled him with hope and given how

00:01:45.400 --> 00:01:50.560
[Amit Varma]: bad the government of the day was, he saw Narendra Modi as a way out. He joined the

00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:57.240
[Amit Varma]: BJP in 2013 and went to see Modi's parliamentary campaign in Varanasi in 2014 from up close.

00:01:57.240 --> 00:02:02.320
[Amit Varma]: He then did a LAMP fellowship, getting deeper insights into how parliament works, or often

00:02:02.320 --> 00:02:07.120
[Amit Varma]: doesn't work. He then took his data analytics skill to be a backroom boy for the political

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:11.960
[Amit Varma]: consultant Prashant Kishore. He did a ton of work at the grassroots, getting Amrindar

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:18.840
[Amit Varma]: Singh elected in Punjab in 2017, rebranding him from Maharaj to Captain. He then realised

00:02:18.840 --> 00:02:23.520
[Amit Varma]: that political consultants were just glorified event managers and decided he would learn

00:02:23.520 --> 00:02:28.840
[Amit Varma]: more by working within a political party. He helped run the BJP's campaign in Manipur

00:02:28.840 --> 00:02:35.920
[Amit Varma]: and Tripura, harnessing new media to do micro-targeting of voters. Then he realised that the BJP didn't

00:02:35.920 --> 00:02:41.040
[Amit Varma]: really care about development, all that was rhetoric and he saw the extent of their divisive

00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:46.200
[Amit Varma]: politics. He quit the party. He even wrote a post about why he quit the party which then

00:02:46.200 --> 00:02:52.520
[Amit Varma]: went viral. Most importantly for us, he wrote his excellent book, How to Win an Indian Election,

00:02:52.520 --> 00:02:58.980
[Amit Varma]: which is so full of deep insights about the nitty-gritties of how our parties run elections.

00:02:58.980 --> 00:03:03.960
[Amit Varma]: His new book, The Art of Conjuring Alternate Realities, is full of the nitty-gritties of

00:03:03.960 --> 00:03:09.520
[Amit Varma]: how narratives are constructed and why we believe them. I'm sure you'll find this conversation

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:15.440
[Amit Varma]: as fascinating as I did. But before we begin, let's take a quick commercial break.

